ense of place and belonging in twentieth-century Canada. The second part, "Inscriptions," in turn explores how ordinary Canadians have embedded their memories of place in oral stories, photographs, and the landscape itself. With its focus on the materiality of image, text, and artefact, these essays argue for an understanding of place as imagined, made, claimed, fought for, and defended � always in a state of becoming.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh1 aEvenden, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGentile, Patrizia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHigh, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Russell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcAllister, Kirsten Emiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Cecilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOpp, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOpp, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRipmeester, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwartz, Joan M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwyripa, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalsh, John C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalsh, John C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Up